  "prompt": "Why is it not possible for one to use 4 pairs of dry cells especially 12 volts to start a car when 12 volts of a wet cell can start a car?",
  "response": "There are several important differences between dry cells (like alkaline batteries) and wet cell car batteries that make dry cells unsuitable for starting a car:\n\n1. Current Capacity\n- Car batteries are designed to deliver high current (300-700 cold cranking amps)\n- Dry cells have very low current delivery capability\n- Car batteries can supply hundreds of amps momentarily; dry cells cannot\n\n2. Internal Resistance\n- Car batteries have very low internal resistance\n- Dry cells have high internal resistance, which limits current flow\n- This means dry cells would heat up and potentially fail when trying to start an engine\n\n3. Discharge Characteristics\n- Car batteries are designed for high momentary current delivery\n- Dry cells quickly lose voltage and capacity under high current demands\n- They would drain almost instantly when attempting to start an engine\n\n4. Construction\n- Car batteries have large, robust lead plates with low resistance\n- Dry cells have smaller, less robust internal components\n- Car batteries are specifically engineered for automotive starting requirements\n\n5. Cost and Practicality\n- Multiple dry cell batteries would be much more expensive\n- They would be bulky and difficult to arrange compared to a single car battery\n\nThese differences make dry cells fundamentally unsuitable for starting a car, despite having similar nominal voltage.",
